    <insight>
        <p>
            The limits within which the area of the textbook lie is found by finding the maximum and minimum area of the textbook.
        </p>
        <p>
            The maximum area is found by multiplying the maximum length and the maximum width, while the minimum area is found by multiplying the minimum length and the minimum width.
        </p>
        <p>
            The absolute error is found by subtracting the actual area from the maximum area, while the relative error is found by dividing the absolute error by the actual area.
        </p>
        <p>
            The percentage error is found by multiplying the relative error by <m>100 \%</m>.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->
     <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The radius and height of a cylindrical mug are <m>4.5</m> cm and <m>8.2</m> cm respectively. Find the limits within which its capacity lies (leave your answer in terms of <m>\pi</m>).
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Capacity of a cylinder is given by the formula <m>V = \pi r^2 h</m>, where <m>r</m> is the radius and <m>h</m> is the height. The maximum and minimum capacity of the mug is given by:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Maximum} \; \amp = \; \pi (4.55)^2 (8.25)\;\text{cm}^3 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; 170.8 \pi \;\text{cm}^3 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Minimum} \; \amp = \; \pi (4.45)^2 (8.15) \;\text{cm}^3</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; 160.4 \pi \;\text{cm}^3 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
     </example>
     <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The measurements of a rectangular card is given as <m>10.3</m> cm by <m>5.2</m> cm. Find:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The absolute error in the area of the card.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The relative error in the area of the card.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The percentage error in the area of the card.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The limits within which the measurements lie are <m>10.25 \leq l \leq 10.35</m> cm, and <m>5.15 \leq w \leq 5.25</m> cm. The working area of the card is given by <m>A = l \times w</m>, where <m>l</m> is the length and <m>w</m> is the width. The maximum and minimum area of the card is given by:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \text{Maximum} \; \amp = \; 10.35 \times 5.25 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \; 54.34 \;\text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \text{Minimum} \; \amp = \; 10.25 \times 5.15 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \; 52.79 \;\text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \text{Working area} \; \amp = \; 10.3 \times 5.2 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \; 53.56 \;\text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \text{Absolute error} \; = \text{Maximum} - \text{Working area} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \; 54.34 - 53.56 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \; 0.78 \;\text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The relative error in the area of the card.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \text{Relative error} \; \amp = \; \frac{\text{Absolute error}}{\text{Working area}}  </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \; \frac{0.78}{53.56} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \; 0.01456 </mrow>
                            </md>
                            
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The percentage error in the area of the card.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \text{Percentage error} \; \amp = \; \text{Absolute error} \times 100 \% </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \; 0.01456 \times 100 \% </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \; 1.456 \% </mrow>
                            </md>
                            
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            
        </solution>
     </example>
     <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The dimmensions of a rectangle are <m>10</m> cm and <m>15</m> cm. If there is an error of <m>5 \% </m> in each of the measurements, Find the percentage error in the area of the rectangle.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Maximum length} \; \amp = \; 15 + \frac{5}{100} \times 15 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; 15 + 0.75 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; 15.75 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Maximum width} \; \amp = \; 10 + \frac{5}{100} \times 10 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; 10 + 0.5 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; 10.5 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Maximum area} \; \amp = \; 15.75 \times 10.5 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; 165.375 \;\text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Working area} \; \amp = \; 15 \times 10 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; 150 \;\text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Absolute error} \; \amp = \;165.375 - 150 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \;15.375 \;\text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Percentage error} \; \amp = \; \frac{\text{Absolute error}}{\text{Working area}} \times 100 \% </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; \frac{15.375}{150} \times 100 \% </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; 10.25 \% </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
     </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- If STACK questions are included, uncomment this: -->

    <!-- <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/checkpoint.ptx" /> -->

    <!-- Add STACK exercises if made -->

    <!-- Add static exercises -->

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the percentage error in the calculation of the volume of a sphere with a radius of <m>4.9</m> cm.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>3.06 \%</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                  The dimension of a box of matches are stated as <m>5.2</m> cm <m>\times 3.8</m> cm <m>\times 1.5</m> cm. Within which limit does its:   
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Volume lie.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Surface area lie.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               <md>
                                    <mrow> \text{Min} \; \amp = \; 28.00 \text{ cm}^3 </mrow>
                                    <mrow> \text{Max} \; \amp = \; 31.33 \text{ cm}^3 </mrow>

                                </md> 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> \text{Min} \; \amp = \; 64.435 \text{ cm}^2 </mrow>
                                    <mrow> \text{Max} \; \amp = \; 68.635 \text{ cm}^2 </mrow>

                                </md> 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A triangle ABC is right angled at B, with <m> AB = 5 \text{ cm} </m>, <m> BC = 12 \text{ cm} </m>, to the nearest centimeter. Find the percentage error (to 4 s.f.) in the calculation of the area of the triangle using the formulae:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>A = \frac{1}{2} \times b \times h </m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>A = \sqrt{s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)} </m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p> The hypotenuse AC is measured as <m>13 \text{ cm} </m> to the nearest centimeter, and the angle <m>\angle BCA</m> is measured as <m>23^\circ</m>, to the nearest degree.  Find the percentage error (to 4 s.f.) in the calculation of the area of the triangle using the formula:
                                <m> A = \frac{1}{2} \times BC \times AC \times \sin \angle BCA </m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Which of these methods is most accurate? Why do you think this is the case?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Working area:
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> A_0 \amp = \frac{1}{2} \times 5 \times 12 </mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp = 30\text{ cm}^2 </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Since the measurements are to the nearest centimeter,
                                <m>4.5 \leq AB \leq 5.5</m>, <m>11.5 \leq BC \leq 12.5</m>.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> A_{\max} \amp = \frac{1}{2} \times 5.5 \times 12.5 </mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp = 34.375\text{ cm}^2 </mrow>
                                    <mrow> \text{Absolute error} \amp = A_{\max} - A_0 </mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp = 34.375 - 30 </mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp = 4.375 </mrow>
                                    <mrow> \text{Percentage error} \amp = \frac{4.375}{30} \times 100\% </mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp = 14.58\% </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Using Heron's formula <m>A = \sqrt{s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)}</m>:
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Working sides are <m>a=5</m>, <m>b=12</m>, <m>c=\sqrt{5^2+12^2}=13</m>.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> s_0 \amp = \frac{5+12+13}{2} </mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp = 15 </mrow>
                                    <mrow> A_0 \amp = \sqrt{15(15-5)(15-12)(15-13)} </mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp = 30\text{ cm}^2 </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                At upper limits: <m>a=5.5</m>, <m>b=12.5</m>,
                                <m>c=\sqrt{5.5^2+12.5^2}=13.6565\ldots</m>.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> s_{\max} \amp = \frac{5.5+12.5+13.6565\ldots}{2} </mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp = 15.8283\ldots </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> A_{\max} \amp = \sqrt{s_{\max}(s_{\max}-5.5)(s_{\max}-12.5)(s_{\max}-13.6565\ldots)} </mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp = 34.375\text{ cm}^2 </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> \text{Percentage error} \amp = \frac{34.375-30}{30}\times 100\% </mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp = 14.583\ldots\% </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>\therefore\; 14.58\%</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Using <m>A = \frac{1}{2}\times BC\times AC\times \sin\angle BCA</m>, and treating all measured quantities as having error.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Working values are <m>BC=12</m>, <m>AC=13</m>, <m>\angle BCA=23^\circ</m>.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> A_0 \amp = \frac{1}{2}\times 12\times 13\times \sin 23^\circ </mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp = 30.477\ldots\text{ cm}^2 </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Since measurements are to the nearest unit,
                                <m>11.5\le BC\le 12.5</m>,
                                <m>12.5\le AC\le 13.5</m>,
                                <m>22.5^\circ\le C\le 23.5^\circ</m>.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> A_{\max} \amp = \frac{1}{2}\times 12.5\times 13.5\times\sin 23.5^\circ </mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp = 33.6445\ldots\text{ cm}^2 </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> A_{\min} \amp = \frac{1}{2}\times 11.5\times 12.5\times\sin 22.5^\circ </mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp = 27.5104\ldots\text{ cm}^2 </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> \text{Maximum absolute error} \amp = \max(A_{\max}-A_0,\,A_0-A_{\min}) </mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp = 3.1674\ldots </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> \text{Percentage error} \amp = \frac{3.1674\ldots}{30.4770\ldots}\times 100\% </mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp = 10.39\ldots\% </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>\therefore\; 10.39\%</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The most accurate method here is part <m>(c)</m>, with percentage error <m>10.39\%</m>, which is smaller than parts <m>(a)</m> and <m>(b)</m> (both <m>14.58\%</m>). This is because the relative errors in <m>BC</m>, <m>AC</m> and <m>\sin C</m> combine to a smaller overall effect than using <m>AB=5</m>, since 0.5 is a larger percentage of 5 than of 12 or 13. 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>
